organization_name_english: PRESIDENCY OF THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA

metadata.history: The Constitution adopted at the First Session (Sept. 15-28, 1954) of the First National People's Congress (NPC), thus known as the "1954 Constitution," established the post of Chairperson (translated into English as "President" in the current revised Constitution) and its provision pertaining to the post of Chairperson was endorsed by the Second and Third NPC. However Liu Shaoqi, who was elected Chairperson of the People's Republic of China on the Third NPC came under criticism during the Cultural Revolution and was stripped of all his posts within and outside the Communist Party of China (CPC) on Oct. 31, 1968 at the Twelfth Plenary Session of the Eighth CPC. Thus the post of Chairperson became vacant and its functions were assumed by Vice Chairpersons Soon Ching Ling and Dong Biwu. When the 1954 Constitution was revised at the First Session (Jan. 13-17, 1975) of the Fourth NPC, the post of Chairperson was officially abolished. And when the Constitution was further revised at the First Session (Feb. 26-Mar. 5, 1978) of the Fifth NPC, the provision concerning the Chairperson remained deleted. However the Fifth NPC, at its Fifth Session (Nov. 26-Dec. 10, 1982), adopted the 1982 Constitution and restored the post of Chairperson/President which has been occupied up to now.
